This can be that reference!</span></span>

## 

<span key="a191b46dc7e74e11a3d4b7f2de2a039d">**Glossary of terms**</span>

<span key="318b914cb5be426aac6f045184570590"><span offset-key="318b914cb5be426aac6f045184570590:0">Here's a table of terms that you will want to remember not only as you work through this prep work but also during the remainder of your programming career.</span></span>

<span key="3bc1a6c99895462ca9d2f0051d08b0d0">**Term**</span>

<span key="41be81ecf4904161817541ccb29903d1">**Definition**</span>

<span key="9d636a0c034640e38ee4f4a003e6a5e8"><span offset-key="9d636a0c034640e38ee4f4a003e6a5e8:0">absolute path</span></span>

<span key="75ba07987e6546628d03b8515f338ef6"><span offset-key="75ba07987e6546628d03b8515f338ef6:0">A path that refers to a particular location in a file system. Absolute paths are usually written with respect to the file system’s root directory, and begin with either “/” (on Unix) or “\\” (on Microsoft Windows). An example of an absolute path is /home/webdevhub/Downloads which would be the path for the directory that contains downloads for the "webdevhub" account.</span></span>

<span key="4f957935cc644758874fb1b227b80fd0"><span offset-key="4f957935cc644758874fb1b227b80fd0:0">command-line interface</span></span>

<span key="22cec5915ef24cd6839c865844902ca6"><span offset-key="22cec5915ef24cd6839c865844902ca6:0">A user interface based on typing commands that interacts with files and the operating system. On Windows, you will use the Ubuntu environment for that. On macOS, you will use Terminal.</span></span>

<span key="7e834a649f8a4e4c9336bb46a6a8d7ab"><span offset-key="7e834a649f8a4e4c9336bb46a6a8d7ab:0">current working directory</span></span>

<span key="7d4ed8b05eb94a78ba07d34fbf8967b1"><span offset-key="7d4ed8b05eb94a78ba07d34fbf8967b1:0">The directory that relative paths are calculated from; equivalently, the place where files referenced by name only are searched for. The current working directory is usually referred to using the shorthand notation "." (pronounced “dot”).</span></span>

<span key="f5ef57c4e9ca4091a03fb847411ef59f"><span offset-key="f5ef57c4e9ca4091a03fb847411ef59f:0">file system</span></span>

<span key="600c000e1b0242908a101025d0684c46"><span offset-key="600c000e1b0242908a101025d0684c46:0">A set of files and directories. A file system may be spread across many physical devices, or many file systems may be stored on a single physical device; the operating system manages access.</span></span>

<span key="5b9d78581af546b0be6ec1bf6ebc0adc"><span offset-key="5b9d78581af546b0be6ec1bf6ebc0adc:0">filename extension</span></span>

<span key="43c00914cba94697bae24b9048c7c9ed"><span offset-key="43c00914cba94697bae24b9048c7c9ed:0">The portion of a file’s name that comes after the final “.” character. By convention this identifies the file’s type: .txt means “text" file, .png means “Portable Network Graphics" file, and so on. These conventions are not enforced by most operating systems: it is perfectly possible (but confusing!) to name an MP3 sound file "homepage.html" which makes it look like an HTML file for showing content in a Web browser!</span></span>

<span key="0d89201cdbe64145a18e977c58de6943"><span offset-key="0d89201cdbe64145a18e977c58de6943:0">home directory</span></span>

<span key="65d92e408a584c8083308e2856970e42"><span offset-key="65d92e408a584c8083308e2856970e42:0">The default directory associated with an account on a computer system. By convention for your account, all of your files are stored in or below your home directory. On macOS, that is found in the /Users/«your-name»k directory. On Ubuntu, you can find your home directory under /home/«your-name». On Windows, you will find it under C:\\Users\\«your-name». On Ubuntu and macOS, the shortcut for your home directory is "~".</span></span>

<span key="d5e0dab3d4f341b196c1363872bca13a"><span offset-key="d5e0dab3d4f341b196c1363872bca13a:0">operating system</span></span>

<span key="b35c7072f1484170b8265753cb966faa"><span offset-key="b35c7072f1484170b8265753cb966faa:0">Software that manages interactions between users, hardware, and software processes. Common examples are Linux, macOS, and Windows.</span></span>

<span key="e7477270cc4f4981aa5fe3ab53ce23cb"><span offset-key="e7477270cc4f4981aa5fe3ab53ce23cb:0">parent directory</span></span>

<span key="959b5ba36ecd4678bfc84b2a8a5f8658"><span offset-key="959b5ba36ecd4678bfc84b2a8a5f8658:0">The directory that “contains” the one in question. Every directory in a file system except the root directory has a parent. A directory’s parent is usually referred to using the shorthand notation ".." (pronounced “dot dot”).</span></span>

<span key="1cd46202cd4e4c9f8e2646da39f5584e"><span offset-key="1cd46202cd4e4c9f8e2646da39f5584e:0">path</span></span>

<span key="4f7c7f341e8e485a9767809945e6201a"><span offset-key="4f7c7f341e8e485a9767809945e6201a:0">A unique description that specifies the location of a file or directory within a file system. There are two kinds of paths: absolute paths and relative paths.</span></span>

<span key="ebb1f555ac5a4078973fb9e850273ae3"><span offset-key="ebb1f555ac5a4078973fb9e850273ae3:0">relative path</span></span>

<span key="b460230c7ac2464689f8cc7574d2b57f"><span offset-key="b460230c7ac2464689f8cc7574d2b57f:0">A path that specifies the location of a file or directory with respect to the current working directory. Any path that does not begin with a path separator character, "/" on Ubuntu and macOS, is a relative path. The path "Documents/Contracts/" is a relative path from the current working directory into a "Contracts" subdirectory under a "Documents" subdirectory. You know that "Contracts" is a subdirectory because there's another path separator ("/") after it.</span></span>

<span key="96a8703822a94dc3b6f4945915f48f85"><span offset-key="96a8703822a94dc3b6f4945915f48f85:0">root directory</span></span>

<span key="938ba49821e64e02bb53327fd2f0210e"><span offset-key="938ba49821e64e02bb53327fd2f0210e:0">The top-most directory in a file system. On macOS and Ubuntu, its name is "/".</span></span>

<span key="b7a2a55de07f43e7b0edc9d3f243e4b7"><span offset-key="b7a2a55de07f43e7b0edc9d3f243e4b7:0">shell</span></span>

<span key="242ccdd1c78f4cba928385b313a10f75"><span offset-key="242ccdd1c78f4cba928385b313a10f75:0">A command-line interface such as Bash or Z shell that allows you to interact with the operating system.</span></span>

<span key="6170522da1e44a8fab8721d46cd43d14"><span offset-key="6170522da1e44a8fab8721d46cd43d14:0">subdirectory</span></span>

<span key="78f4ecbac4ea4bf1be34e950105b7233"><span offset-key="78f4ecbac4ea4bf1be34e950105b7233:0">A directory contained within another directory. All directories except the root directory are subdirectories.</span></span>

<span key="d87f6d0000924cecaefb3a9c3214b89f"><span offset-key="d87f6d0000924cecaefb3a9c3214b89f:0">wildcard</span></span>

<span key="65b4a52717ba40549feedc1b7bd3b103"><span offset-key="65b4a52717ba40549feedc1b7bd3b103:0">A character used to specify a pattern to match. In Bash or Z shell, the wildcard character "\*" matches zero or more characters. This means that "\*.txt" would match any name that ends with ".txt".</span></span>

<span key="3f4b0f50359d4e798cfbaacaa93f3c5f">*Regarding file extensions: since many applications use filename extensions to identify the MIME type of the file, misnaming files may cause those applications to fail. If you copy a picture from your phone to your computer and rename it "recipes.docx", then your word processor program will probably try to open it and complain that the file is unrecognizable or corrupt. You know that it's just an image, though, because you're smarter than the computer.*</span>
